content":"Select **Terminal** from the dropdown"},"344":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-15","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#open-a-terminal","content":"A new terminal session opens with your default shell"},"345":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-16","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#open-a-terminal","content":"Each terminal is a full PTY session — it runs your actual shell (zsh, bash, fish, etc.) with complete support for colors, cursor movement, and interactive programs like `vim` or `top`."},"346":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-17","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#working-with-tabs","content":"Tabs appear along the top of the workspace. You can:"},"347":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-18","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#working-with-tabs","content":"**Reorder** tabs by dragging them"},"348":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-19","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#working-with-tabs","content":"**Close** a tab by clicking the X or using the keyboard shortcut"},"349":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-20","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#working-with-tabs","content":"**Create** new tabs with the + button — choose from Terminal, Editor, IDE, Web Preview, or Project"},"350":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session-21","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/first-session","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/first-session#working-with-tabs","content":"Each tab type has its own purpose. Terminals run shells, the IDE op